<a href="javascript:card_browser(78)">Goblin Swarms</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(91)">They Are Coming</a> x2<br>
Goblin <a href="javascript:card_browser(303)">Armor</a>y<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(90)">Relics of Moria</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(75)">Goblin Scimitar</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(60)">Denizens Enraged</a> x2<br>
Total 36    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> **Oops!**<br>
I forgot to include the adventure Path in the actual card list, so here you go:<br>
[1]Westfarthing<br>
[2]Midgewater Moors<br>
[3]Council Courtyard<br>
[4]Moria Stairway<br>
[5]Bridge of Khazad-Dum<br>
[6]Galadriel&#39;s Glade<br>
[7]Anduin Wilderland<br>
[8]Shores of Nen Hithoel<br>
[9]Summit of Amon Hen<br>
<br>
<br>
Ok, this deck has presently been overhauled a little for Mines. Nothing too major, but let&#39;s have a look at what this deck does best: Card advantage. Not simply card quantity, but card quality, which it does two ways: The ability to select which cards go into your hand, and recursion. Alot of recursion. It&#39;s about finding that favorite foil of yours and being able to play it over and over again. Goblin Swarms, Barliman, Questions that Need Answering, and Host of Thousands all add up to one dead opponent. So we&#39;ll start with Fellowship:<br>
Preemptively, before anyone can say anything; this is a Gandalf deck. It does not start Gandalf, I know, but it has six cards for getting Gandalf (4 copies of Gandalf, and 2 A Wizard is Never Late) out of 72. That&#39;s something like one in twelve; actually, it&#39;s exactly one in twelve. So, assuming you take out 2 cards for my starting fellowship, then 8 cards for my opening hand and, if I&#39;ve done my maths correctly, I should get Gandalf or the means to get Gandalf before I head for site 3. And, assuming something awful goes wrong, my deck chokes out pretty well, and the only thing it has to really fear is Nazgul, which is why I field the uncommon version of Legolas, as his bonus for Nazgul is really helpful. <br>
<br>
Questions that Need Answering has fared very well for me, because pitching, say, Moria minions is not a problem because of how well they recur, and it is raw card advantage. I had heard someone mention it being the most useless Rare Gandalf gets, and personally I think it&#39;s rather powerful, and is making me consider using Ottar for a cart deck I&#39;m working on, but that&#39;s another story. Shadow side strategy now.<br>
<br>
Goes without saying: Swarm. Hold off a little until they step underground, then jump them, and keep a couple of principles in mind: An exertion is as good as a wound at site 4. Play the Wallcrawlers at site 4, and, if you can, again at site 5. I run 4 Hosts and two They Are Coming, mostly because the cards I have that I cannot recur; posessions, events, etc., are not things I can afford to pitch unless absolutely necessary, and I&#39;ll still get a They Are Coming out by site 6 when it starts getting hairy for the opponent. Would like to add another Armory when I get one for the Shadow pool advantage.  So that&#39;s it; bid low, going first isn&#39;t a big deal, don&#39;t play yourself out early with the Goblins, don&#39;t use your Gandalf events until you need to, a Servant in the hand is worth four in the graveyard, until you get Barliman.  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=21975"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=21975" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
